<rss version="2.0" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/"><channel><title>智能新闻| smithsonianmag.com</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/rss/smart-news/</link><description>智能新闻的 RSS 提要</description><lastBuildDate>Sun, 26 Apr 2026 12:40:03 GMT</lastBuildDate><generator>rfeed v1.1.1</generator><docs>https://github.com/svpino/rfeed/blob/master/README.md</docs><item><title>国家许可的医用大麻已被重新归类为危险性较低的药物。这就是这意味着什么</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/state-licensed-medical-marijuana-has-been-reclassified-as-a-less-dangerous-drug-heres-what-that-means-180988617/</link><description>此举将使研究人员更容易研究该物质，并为获得许可的医用大麻经销商提供税收减免</description><pubDate>Fri, 24 Apr 2026 20:32:48 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/state-licensed-medical-marijuana-has-been-reclassified-as-a-less-dangerous-drug-heres-what-that-means-180988617/</guid></item><item><title>世界上第一家人工智能艺术博物馆将在洛杉矶开幕，艺术界正在思考道德和可持续发展问题</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/the-worlds-first-museum-of-ai-art-will-open-in-los-angeles-as-the-art-world-ponders-questions-of-ethics-and-sustainability-180988613/</link><description>Dataland 的沉浸式展览由人工智能生成，将于 6 月 20 日向公众首次亮相，首场展览以数百万张自然图像为基础，介绍雨林</description><pubDate>Fri, 24 Apr 2026 20:28:04 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/the-worlds-first-museum-of-ai-art-will-open-in-los-angeles-as-the-art-world-ponders-questions-of-ethics-and-sustainability-180988613/</guid></item><item><title>为了让航海者一号航天器继续其星际之旅，美国宇航局关闭了其为数不多的剩余仪器之一</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/to-keep-the-voyager-1-spacecraft-on-its-interstellar-journey-nasa-turned-off-one-of-its-few-remaining-instruments-180988608/</link><description>该探测器于近 50 年前发射，是距离地球最远的人造物体。关闭其中一台科学设备将有助于其节省能源并继续向太阳系边缘行进</description><pubDate>Fri, 24 Apr 2026 18:59:13 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/to-keep-the-voyager-1-spacecraft-on-its-interstellar-journey-nasa-turned-off-one-of-its-few-remaining-instruments-180988608/</guid></item><item><title>我们为什么喜欢电影？这家新的“智能”电影院可追踪观众的脑电波和心率以找出答案</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/this-new-smart-movie-theatre-is-tracking-audiences-brain-waves-and-heart-rates-to-create-more-engaging-films-180988614/</link><description>布里斯托大学的研究人员正在通过将一家剧院变成生物识别实验室来研究电影观看体验的吸引力</description><pubDate>Fri, 24 Apr 2026 18:20:25 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/this-new-smart-movie-theatre-is-tracking-audiences-brain-waves-and-heart-rates-to-create-more-engaging-films-180988614/</guid></item><item><title>海狸是生态系统工程师，它们可能成为对抗人为气候变化的有用盟友</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/beavers-are-ecosystem-engineers-and-they-might-be-helpful-allies-in-the-fight-against-human-caused-climate-change-180988609/</link><description>新的研究表明，勤劳的啮齿动物创造的湿地是碳汇，这意味着它们储存了大量的吸热二氧化碳——人类产生的气体是当今全球变暖的主要原因</description><pubDate>Fri, 24 Apr 2026 14:36:06 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/beavers-are-ecosystem-engineers-and-they-might-be-helpful-allies-in-the-fight-against-human-caused-climate-change-180988609/</guid></item><item><title>是什么杀死了尼安德特人？新研究表明缺乏遗传多样性可能是部分原因</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/what-killed-the-neanderthals-new-research-suggests-a-lack-of-genetic-diversity-may-be-partially-to-blame-180988612/</link><description>当气候变冷时，尼安德特人的人口减少了。大多数生活在 60,000 至 40,000 年前的生物都是同一血统的后裔，并且具有非常相似的 DNA</description><pubDate>Fri, 24 Apr 2026 14:04:18 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/what-killed-the-neanderthals-new-research-suggests-a-lack-of-genetic-diversity-may-be-partially-to-blame-180988612/</guid></item><item><title>在欧洲和非洲之间的沉船墓地，考古学家发现了数千年来注定沉没的船只</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/in-a-graveyard-of-shipwrecks-between-europe-and-africa-archaeologists-discovered-vessels-doomed-over-thousands-of-years-180988605/</link><description>一项新的考古调查显示，直布罗陀海峡的“港口”是古罗马、中世纪和二战沉船的最后安息地</description><pubDate>Fri, 24 Apr 2026 10:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/in-a-graveyard-of-shipwrecks-between-europe-and-africa-archaeologists-discovered-vessels-doomed-over-thousands-of-years-180988605/</guid></item><item><title>日本找到了 1200 年樱花数据的新管家，维持气候变化研究项目</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/in-japan-a-new-steward-for-1200-years-of-cherry-blossom-data-has-been-found-sustaining-a-climate-change-research-project-180988607/</link><description>去年夏天去世的气候科学家青野康幸学会了阅读古代日本文字，以汇编可追溯到公元九世纪的盛花期记录</description><pubDate>Thu, 23 Apr 2026 20:56:07 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/in-japan-a-new-steward-for-1200-years-of-cherry-blossom-data-has-been-found-sustaining-a-climate-change-research-project-180988607/</guid></item><item><title>火星探测器发现了这颗红色星球上前所未见的生命基石，为古代宜居性提供了证据</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/a-mars-rover-found-building-blocks-of-life-never-seen-on-the-red-planet-before-boosting-the-case-for-ancient-habitability-180988610/</link><description>美国宇航局好奇号探测器发现的有机分子可能是由生命形成的，但它们也可能来自地质过程或陨石</description><pubDate>Thu, 23 Apr 2026 20:10:15 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/a-mars-rover-found-building-blocks-of-life-never-seen-on-the-red-planet-before-boosting-the-case-for-ancient-habitability-180988610/</guid></item><item><title>直布罗陀著名的猴子正在吃泥土，可能会缓解因咀嚼游客垃圾食品而引起的胃痛</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/gibraltars-famous-monkeys-are-eating-dirt-likely-to-alleviate-stomach-aches-from-munching-on-tourists-junk-food-180988606/</link><description>英国境内的巴巴里猕猴是欧洲唯一的野生猴子。但许多人正在食用热量、糖、盐和乳制品含量高、纤维含量低的人类零食</description><pubDate>Thu, 23 Apr 2026 19:51:11 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/gibraltars-famous-monkeys-are-eating-dirt-likely-to-alleviate-stomach-aches-from-munching-on-tourists-junk-food-180988606/</guid></item><item><title>十年来首次在洪都拉斯山脉发现罕见的“云美洲虎”，代表环保主义者的胜利</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/a-rare-cloud-jaguar-was-spotted-in-honduran-mountains-for-the-first-time-in-a-decade-representing-a-win-for-conservationists-180988595/</link><description>这种大型猫科动物很少出现在高海拔地区，因此这一目击事件表明保护该地区野生动物走廊的努力正在发挥作用</description><pubDate>Thu, 23 Apr 2026 15:37:16 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/a-rare-cloud-jaguar-was-spotted-in-honduran-mountains-for-the-first-time-in-a-decade-representing-a-win-for-conservationists-180988595/</guid></item><item><title>考古学家在 1,600 年前的埃及木乃伊包裹物中挖掘出《伊利亚特》的纸莎草碎片</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/archaeologists-unearth-a-papyrus-fragment-from-the-iliad-tucked-inside-the-wrappings-of-a-1600-year-old-egyptian-mummy-180988603/</link><description>荷马史诗的摘录以他的船只目录为特色，这是一段著名的段落，列出了航行到特洛伊的希腊军队。这可能是在木乃伊化背景下发现的第一个希腊文学文本</description><pubDate>Thu, 23 Apr 2026 15:07:03 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/archaeologists-unearth-a-papyrus-fragment-from-the-iliad-tucked-inside-the-wrappings-of-a-1600-year-old-egyptian-mummy-180988603/</guid></item><item><title>可卡因污染似乎使鲑鱼比平常游得更远。科学家们不知道长期后果</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/cocaine-pollution-seems-to-make-salmon-swim-faster-and-farther-than-usual-scientists-dont-know-the-long-term-consequences-180988600/</link><description>这种非法药物的主要副产品苯甲酰爱康宁比可卡因本身产生更强烈的影响。废水处理厂通常不会完全处理此类代谢物，因此它们在水体中的浓度经常高于其母体药物</description><pubDate>Thu, 23 Apr 2026 14:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/cocaine-pollution-seems-to-make-salmon-swim-faster-and-farther-than-usual-scientists-dont-know-the-long-term-consequences-180988600/</guid></item><item><title>50 年前，一对来自墨西哥的夫妇成为洛杉矶软塔可的先驱。现在，他们的餐厅已成为地标</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/a-couple-from-mexico-became-soft-taco-pioneers-in-los-angeles-50-years-ago-now-their-restaurant-is-a-landmark-180988602/</link><description>劳尔 (Raúl) 和卢佩·马丁内斯 (Lupe Martinez) 打开 King Taco，端上软玉米饼，就像他们在家乡记忆中一样。由于洛杉矶市议会的投票，剩下的事情现在已经正式成为历史</description><pubDate>Thu, 23 Apr 2026 13:26:28 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/a-couple-from-mexico-became-soft-taco-pioneers-in-los-angeles-50-years-ago-now-their-restaurant-is-a-landmark-180988602/</guid></item><item><title>国家美术馆接受了借阅图书馆的新角色，感谢向其他博物馆发送艺术品的大礼</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/the-national-gallery-of-art-embraces-new-role-as-lending-library-thanks-to-a-big-gift-that-sends-artwork-to-other-museums-180988597/</link><description>长期受托人米切尔·P·拉尔斯 (Mitchell P. Rales) 的家族基金会捐赠 1.16 亿美元，用于分享博物馆的藏品，以纪念美国 250 岁生日</description><pubDate>Wed, 22 Apr 2026 21:03:15 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/the-national-gallery-of-art-embraces-new-role-as-lending-library-thanks-to-a-big-gift-that-sends-artwork-to-other-museums-180988597/</guid></item><item><title>仿人机器人在中国比赛中打破了人类最快半程马拉松世界纪录</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/a-humanoid-robot-just-beat-the-human-world-record-for-the-fastest-half-marathon-during-a-race-in-china-180988599/</link><description>由中国电子公司荣耀开发的名为“闪电”的自动导航机器人赢得了 13.1 英里的比赛。其成绩和其他成绩标志着自去年首届赛事以来取得的重大进步，当时 21 名机器人中只有 6 人到达了终点线</description><pubDate>Wed, 22 Apr 2026 19:27:47 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/a-humanoid-robot-just-beat-the-human-world-record-for-the-fastest-half-marathon-during-a-race-in-china-180988599/</guid></item><item><title>旧金山的稀有硬币寻宝游戏为参与者提供了重温加州淘金热的机会</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/this-rare-coin-scavenger-hunt-in-san-francisco-offers-participants-the-chance-to-relive-the-california-gold-rush-180988598/</link><description>当地一家硬币经销商将在 4 月 25 日举办的第三届年度全市挑战赛中隐藏价值总计 50,000 美元的历史货币</description><pubDate>Wed, 22 Apr 2026 18:42:31 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/this-rare-coin-scavenger-hunt-in-san-francisco-offers-participants-the-chance-to-relive-the-california-gold-rush-180988598/</guid></item><item><title>人类仍在进化。一项研究表明，自然选择青睐与红头发和较少男性型秃发有关的基因</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/humans-are-still-evolving-natural-selection-has-favored-genes-linked-to-red-hair-and-less-male-pattern-baldness-a-study-suggests-180988563/</link><description>对数千名西欧亚人的古代和现代 DNA 进行的大规模研究发现了近 500 种近代历史上进化选择支持或反对的遗传变异</description><pubDate>Wed, 22 Apr 2026 17:34:32 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/humans-are-still-evolving-natural-selection-has-favored-genes-linked-to-red-hair-and-less-male-pattern-baldness-a-study-suggests-180988563/</guid></item><item><title>半个多世纪后，鲍勃·迪伦的《我不在那里》的原始打字稿歌词被重新发现</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/bob-dylans-original-typewritten-draft-lyrics-for-im-not-there-have-been-rediscovered-after-more-than-half-a-century-180988592/</link><description>几十年来，热心的歌迷只能在盗版黑胶唱片上听到这首晦涩难懂的歌曲。歌词草稿位于艾伦·金斯伯格 (Allen Ginsberg) 诗歌的第一版副本中，刚刚在拍卖会上以 6,800 美元的价格售出</description><pubDate>Wed, 22 Apr 2026 16:15:00 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/bob-dylans-original-typewritten-draft-lyrics-for-im-not-there-have-been-rediscovered-after-more-than-half-a-century-180988592/</guid></item><item><title>一项研究表明，我们使用许多相同的脑细胞来观察和想象物体。这些发现为了解记忆提供了一个新窗口</title><link>https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/we-use-many-of-the-same-brain-cells-to-see-and-to-imagine-objects-a-study-suggests-the-findings-provide-a-new-window-into-memory-180988580/</link><description>虽然过去的研究暗示相关大脑区域存在重叠，但新的研究深入到了细胞水平。这一发现可能有助于改善记忆障碍（如痴呆症）和某些精神疾病（如精神分裂症）的治疗</description><pubDate>Wed, 22 Apr 2026 14:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/we-use-many-of-the-same-brain-cells-to-see-and-to-imagine-objects-a-study-suggests-the-findings-provide-a-new-window-into-memory-180988580/</guid></item></channel></rss>